Here's my performance review of this truncation library:

---

## Performance Review: `Truncation.cs`

### 🔴 Critical — `FixedNumberOfWordsTruncator.Truncate` (line 178)

```csharp
var words = value.Split(' ', StringSplitOptions.RemoveEmptyEntries);
```

`Split` allocates a `string[]` **plus** a new `string` for every word — even when truncation only needs the first few. On a 500-word body, this is ~501 heap allocations on every call. Combined with `words.Take(length)` (LINQ iterator overhead) and `string.Join` + `+ truncationString` (two more allocations), this is the most expensive hot path in the file.

**Fix:** Count word boundaries by index without splitting. Use `AsSpan` to locate the cut point, then concatenate with `string.Concat(ReadOnlySpan, ReadOnlySpan)`:

```csharp
// Right-truncation: find the end index of the Nth word
int wordCount = 0, endIndex = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < value.Length; i++)
{
    if (value[i] == ' ') continue;
    // start of a word — scan to its end
    while (i < value.Length && value[i] != ' ') i++;
    if (++wordCount == length) { endIndex = i; break; }
}
return string.Concat(value.AsSpan(0, endIndex), truncationString.AsSpan());
```

---

### 🔴 Critical — `Symbols.IsSymbol` / `GetSymbolGroup` (lines 259–287)

`List<char>[]` is a heap-allocated array of heap-allocated lists. `IsSymbol` does a linear scan through every group calling `List<char>.Contains` (itself O(n)) — worst case touches all ~25 characters. This is called per-character in the pipeline.

**Fix:** Replace with a flat lookup. A `SearchValues<char>` (.NET 8+) or a `HashSet<char>` for `IsSymbol`, and a `char → int` dictionary or 128-entry `int[]` lookup table for `GetSymbolGroup`:

```csharp
private static readonly SearchValues<char> AllSymbols =
    SearchValues.Create("()[]{}+-*/=<>!.,;:?!@#$%^&~`\"'\\|");

internal static bool IsSymbol(char c) => AllSymbols.Contains(c);

// For GetSymbolGroup: a flat byte[128] maps ASCII char → group index (0xFF = not found)
```

---

### 🟡 Moderate — `FixedLengthTruncator` right-truncation (line 72)

```csharp
return value[..(length - truncationString.Length)].TrimEnd() + truncationString;
```

Three allocations: substring from range, `TrimEnd()` result, `+` concatenation. The left-truncation path on line 65 correctly uses `AsSpan`-based concat — this path should match:

```csharp
var slice = value.AsSpan(0, length - truncationString.Length).TrimEnd();
return string.Concat(slice, truncationString.AsSpan());
```

`ReadOnlySpan<char>.TrimEnd()` returns a narrowed span with **zero** allocations, reducing this to a single allocation.

---

### 🟢 Minor — LINQ in word truncator (lines 187, 190)

`words.Take(length)` and `words.Skip(...)` add iterator/enumerator overhead on a hot path. If `Split` is retained, use `string.Join(" ", words.AsSpan(0, length))` (the `ReadOnlySpan<string>` overload, .NET 8+) or an explicit loop to avoid LINQ entirely.

---

### Summary

| Issue | Location | Allocations saved per call |
|---|---|---|
| `Split` + LINQ in word truncator | L178–190 | ~N+3 (N = word count) |
| `List<char>[]` symbol lookup | L244–287 | 0 allocs, but ~10× faster lookup |
| Double-alloc right truncation | L72 | 2 |

The word truncator and symbol lookup are the highest-impact fixes for a high-throughput content delivery system.
